05523nam a22008655i 9783110711578DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020951840  a97831107115787 a10.1515/97831107115782doi  a(DE-B1597)562965  a(OCoLC)1248760287  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0060902bisacsh1 aYip, Hei Yin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEzekiel's Message of Hope and Restoration :bRedaction-Critical Study of Ezekiel 1–7 /cHei Yin Yip. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XIV, 283 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die alttestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0934-2575 ;v53200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Introduction -- t2 Ezekiel’s Call Narrative (Ezek 1:1–3:15) -- t3 Ezekiel’s Call to be a Watchman (Ezek 3:16–21) and his Call to Muteness (Ezek 3:22–27) -- t4 Ezekiel’s Sign-Acts -- t5 The Oracle against the Mountains of Israel -- t6 The Oracle concerning the End of the Land of Israel -- t7 The Reassertion of the Legitimacy of the Zadokite Priesthood in the Early Persian Period -- t8 The Relation between the Secondary Material in Ezekiel 6–7 and the Law of the Temple -- t9 Conclusion -- tAppendix A: The Relative Chronology of Ezek 3:22–27 and 37:1–14 -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Scripture References -- tIndex of Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first twenty-four chapters of the book of Ezekiel are characterised by vehement declarations of judgement. This observation leaves the impression that Ezekiel 1–7 is devoid of references to hope and restoration. However, there is a redactional stratum in this section that supplemented the texts with material that conveys restoration and hope for the future. In Ezekiel 1–7, many of these additions focus on priestly topics. The motif of restoration in the redactional material of Ezekiel 3–5 is expressed by the reinstatement of Ezekiel in his priestly role. This editorial emphasis on Ezekiel as priest in the redactional material suggests that the redaction was influenced by Zechariah 3, a text that depicts the reinstitution of the exiled Zadokite priesthood. Moreover, the redactional material of Ezekiel 6-7 drew inspiration from the Law of the Temple in Ezekiel 43-46, as the redactors sought to enhance Ezekiel’s priestly role. The study provides new insights into how redactors, who may have been associated with the Zadokite priesthood, inserted the message of hope and restoration into the literary unit Ezekiel 1-7 during the post-exilic period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aHesekiel. 4aPriestertum. 4aRedaktionskritik. 4aWiederherstellung. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aEzekiel.  apriesthood.  aredaction criticism.  arestoration.1 aYip, Hei Yin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021 Englishz978311075419308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021z9783110753974oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831107116770 cprintz978311071126440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311071